  "local_port": 36252,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I transfer from an international university to a US university as a US permanent resident?",
  "response": "Transferring from an international university to a U.S. university as a U.S. permanent resident involves several steps. Here\u2019s a general process to guide you:\n\n### 1. Research and Identify Potential Universities\n- **Programs and Majors**: Look for U.S. universities that offer programs aligned with your current studies or future career goals.\n- **Transfer Policies**: Check each university\u2019s transfer policies, deadlines, application requirements, and whether they accept transfer students from international institutions.\n\n### 2. Review Accreditation and Transfer Credits\n- **Accreditation**: Ensure your current institution is accredited. U.S. universities typically require that transfer credits come from accredited institutions.\n- **Credit Transfer**: Each university will have its own policy on how many credits they will accept. Be prepared to provide course descriptions, syllabi, and other documentation to support your credit transfer application.\n\n### 3. Prepare Application Materials\n- **Transcripts**: Obtain official transcripts from your current institution. These should be translated into English, if necessary, and may need to be evaluated by a third-party assessment service.\n- **Statement of Purpose**: Write a compelling statement explaining why you want to transfer, your academic and professional goals, and why you\u2019ve chosen that particular university.\n- **Letters of Recommendation**: Request letters from professors or academic advisors who can speak to your abilities and character.\n\n### 4. Standardized Tests (if applicable)\n- Some U.S. universities may require standardized test scores (like the SAT or ACT for undergraduate transfers, or the GRE for graduate transfers). Check requirements for each university.\n\n### 5. Complete Application Process\n- **Online Application**: Fill out the university\u2019s transfer application. Pay attention to deadlines, as they can vary between institutions.\n- **Application Fee**: Be prepared to pay any application fees that are required.\n\n### 6. Financial Considerations\n- **Tuition and Financial Aid**: Understand the tuition and fees at the U.S. university. As a permanent resident, you\u2019ll typically be eligible for in-state tuition at public universities after a certain period.\n- **Scholarships**: Explore scholarship opportunities for transfer students, both specific to the university and external scholarships.\n\n### 7. Apply for a Student Visa (if needed)\n- If you are not currently in the U.S., you may need to apply for a student visa (F-1 visa) for your studies in the U.S. Check if your permanent resident status affects your visa requirements.\n\n### 8. Follow Up\n- **Communicate with Admissions**: Maintain communication with the admissions office to confirm they have received all necessary documents and to ask any questions you may have about the process.\n- **Campus Visits**: If possible, visit the campuses of the schools you are interested in to get a sense of the environment and culture.\n\n### 9. Prepare for Transition\n- If admitted, review orientation information, housing options, and course registration processes to ensure a smooth transition.\n\n### 10. Connect with Current Students\n- Engage with current students or alumni from the departments you\u2019re interested in. They can provide insights about the university experience, help you navigate the transfer process, and assist with adjusting to life in the U.S.\n\nEach university may have specific requirements or additional steps, so it's crucial to closely review the transfer application guidelines for each institution you are considering. Good luck with your transfer!",
